nodes exist in the nodes list. Then I'll perform DFS traversal, tracking node states to detect cycles—if I encounter a gray node during traversal, that indicates a cycle exists. The result will be nodes in reverse finish order. ological order. Then iterate through all nodes, running DFS on any unvisited ones to ensure disconnected components are handled.\n\nThe implementation handles several edge cases: empty graphs return immediately, self-loops and cycles are detected via the color-marking scheme (gray indicates currently visiting), and edges referencing nodes outside the provided list throw errors. I'm also reconsidering the efficiency of using `unshift` to add nodes to the front of the result array—that's O(n²) overall. Instead, I can push nodes during post-order traversal and reverse the final result, which is O(n).",
